**Russian Information Campaigns Soften Internal Fatigue of War, ISW Reports**
Recent Russian internal polls show that the Ukrainian military operation in the Kursk region has not decreased the level of support for the war in Ukraine among Russian citizens in the short term. According to a report by the Institute for the Study of War (ISW), the Russian government's information campaigns have softened the internal fatigue of the war and given flexibility in choosing a strategy for a prolonged war of exhaustion against Ukraine. A recent survey by the Russian sociological organization 'Levada Center' found that around 78% of respondents support Russian military operations in Ukraine, which is more than 75% in July 2024 and 77% in June 2024. ISW analysts note that the 'Levada Center' survey indicates that the lowest level of support for the war among Russians was in February 2022, when 68% of respondents supported the war, and that support for the war among respondents has not fallen below 70% since March 2022. The 'Levada Center' also asked respondents about the Ukrainian operation in the Kursk region and found that 91% of respondents were concerned about Ukrainian military operations on Russian territory. 'Levada Center' also reported that 57% of respondents do not expect a second wave of mobilization, and 60% do not see the need for a second wave of mobilization in the coming months - both indicators decreased from 65% and 69% respectively. According to the ISW report, 'The data from the 'Levada Center' survey indicates that the Kremlin's refusal to fully shift Russian society to a war footing and ongoing internal information campaigns by the Kremlin to normalize the war in Russian society have so far softened internal fatigue of the war, and that the Ukrainian operation in the Kursk region has not changed these attitudes.' ISW emphasized that the fact that Russian society as a whole 'does not feel fatigue from the war, likely gives the Kremlin flexibility in choosing a strategy for a prolonged war of exhaustion against Ukraine.'
