**Kremlin Prepares Russians for 'New Normalcy' Amid Prolonged Ukrainian Military Advance**
The Kremlin is preparing Russians for a 'new normalcy' with a prolonged Ukrainian military advance and the involvement of conscripts in the fighting. According to sources close to the administration of President Vladimir Putin and the government, the initial shock of the Ukrainian operation in the Kursk region has worn off, and people are adapting to the situation. 'During the shock, there are always jumps in sociological indicators, but soon people get used to it, and the situation stabilizes,' said one of the sources. To accelerate the adaptation of citizens to the new reality, the Kremlin is actively using propaganda to prepare Russians for life in the conditions of the so-called 'new normalcy' - a concept that was already used during the COVID-19 pandemic and at the beginning of the war with Ukraine. 'This is necessary so that people perceive what is happening as not a deviation, but a new norm, although temporary. In the new norm, it is easier to exist,' explained a media technologist who cooperates with the internal policy block of the administration of the President. The Kremlin is trying to form a 'new reality' through several key messages: citizens are being encouraged to 'redirect negative and shock into a positive direction,' including participating in the collection of aid for the Kursk region. The administration of the President has already recommended to the regional authorities to organize such events. Sources interviewed by 'Meduza' believe that the battles in the Kursk region may last for several months. However, a source close to the government warns that this forecast is 'quite optimistic, if everything goes well.' Sources close to the Kremlin confirm that after the start of the operation, the possibility of a new wave of mobilization was considered. This is also confirmed by sources from Bloomberg, stating that a new mobilization may be announced by the end of 2024 due to a lack of reserves. However, a source close to the government states that the Cabinet of Ministers and representatives of the large business are against mobilization, as it may hit the economy. 'This will drain the last labor resources from the economy. Nobody is working anymore. And then they will take some, and others will start hiding,' he explained. At the same time, the interlocutor emphasizes that it is unclear how such arguments will be taken into account by the higher leadership of the country. He adds that it is more likely that conscripts will be involved in the battles in the Kursk region, and media preparation of the public for this is already underway. It is also noted that Russian 'elites' are expecting the resignation of those responsible for the breakthrough of the Ukrainian military on Russian territory.
