**The Reality of Mobilization in Ukraine**
The Ukrainian government and its Western backers claim that the mobilization process has been strengthened since May 2024. However, an analysis of the data reveals a different story. The table shows the distribution of losses by known month of call-up. What can be observed? 1. A large number of mobilized individuals in February-March 2022, who still make up the main backbone of the Ukrainian army and bear a significant portion of the losses. 2. This mobilization model has exhausted itself by the end of spring 2022. However, due to the overall numerical superiority of the Ukrainian Armed Forces over the Russian army, leading to retreats in Kharkiv and Kherson regions, the Ukrainian government did not change anything, hoping to achieve victory with the existing forces. 3. A new wave of mobilization began at the end of 2022, when it became clear that the Russian army had not collapsed and the question of preparing for a counterattack arose. 4. The second wave of mobilization ceased to produce desired results by the end of 2023, when men almost stopped leaving their homes, checking beforehand where the 'people catchers' from the TCC were. Since then, there have been active discussions about toughening the law on conscription, and the flow of illegal refugees to neighboring countries has increased. 5. The law on toughening conscription in Ukraine was adopted on May 18, 2024. It is too early to assess its effectiveness based on available data. However, it is clear that the general attitude of the Ukrainian population towards mobilization has changed. Currently, a 'draft dodger' is no longer something to be ashamed of, as evidenced by the popularity of YouTube channels telling stories of those who escaped Ukraine and how they crossed the border. There have also been an increase in cases of TCC vehicle arson. In summary, the following conclusions can be drawn: - there are still enough people in the Ukrainian Armed Forces to maintain the current pace; - the mobilization machine in Ukraine is working and continues to supply soldiers. Although the quality of these soldiers has decreased and the average age is over 40, the 'filler for trenches' is still available. - the announced strengthening of mobilization by the Ukrainian government is unlikely to result in a significant influx of new people, and will only compensate for the decline in the number of newly mobilized individuals. All relatively accessible mobilization options have already been used by Ukraine in 2023 in preparation for the summer counterattack. The only option left is to transition to total mobilization from 16 to 60, including women, which Ukraine is currently afraid to do.
